6Ô∏è‚É£ Embedded Linux Boot Flow

Full boot sequence:

Power ON
   ‚Üì
Boot ROM
   ‚Üì
Bootloader (U-Boot / GRUB)
   ‚Üì
Kernel loads
   ‚Üì
Initramfs mounts
   ‚Üì
Root filesystem mounts
   ‚Üì
Init system starts
   ‚Üì
Services/apps start

Same flow used in switches.

‚∏ª

7Ô∏è‚É£ Boot Components Explained

‚∏ª

Boot ROM

Hardware internal firmware.

Loads first bootloader.

‚∏ª

Bootloader

Examples:
	‚Ä¢	U-Boot
	‚Ä¢	GRUB

Responsibilities:
	‚Ä¢	Load kernel
	‚Ä¢	Pass boot args
	‚Ä¢	Select boot image

‚∏ª

Kernel

Core OS brain.

Handles:
	‚Ä¢	CPU scheduling
	‚Ä¢	Memory
	‚Ä¢	Drivers
	‚Ä¢	Interrupts

‚∏ª

Root Filesystem (rootfs)

Contains:
	‚Ä¢	/bin
	‚Ä¢	/sbin
	‚Ä¢	/lib
	‚Ä¢	/etc
	‚Ä¢	/usr

All system utilities.

‚∏ª

8Ô∏è‚É£ Embedded Linux Filesystems

Common types:

FS	Usage
ext4	Writable storage
squashfs	Read-only firmware
cramfs	Compressed images
tmpfs	RAM filesystem
ubifs	NAND flash

DiagOS often uses squashfs + tmpfs.

‚∏ª

9Ô∏è‚É£ Device Drivers in Embedded Linux

Drivers enable hardware:

Examples in switches:
	‚Ä¢	I¬≤C driver ‚Üí EEPROM
	‚Ä¢	PCIe driver ‚Üí ASIC
	‚Ä¢	GPIO driver ‚Üí LEDs/fans
	‚Ä¢	MDIO driver ‚Üí PHY

Without drivers ‚Üí hardware unusable.

‚∏ª

üîü BSP (Board Support Package)

Embedded Linux requires BSP.

BSP provides:
	‚Ä¢	Kernel config
	‚Ä¢	Drivers
	‚Ä¢	Boot configs
	‚Ä¢	Device tree
	‚Ä¢	Platform mapping

BSP makes Linux run on specific board.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Device Tree (DTS)

Defines hardware layout.

Example:

I2C buses
GPIO pins
EEPROM address
Fan controllers

Kernel reads DTS ‚Üí knows hardware topology.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Build Systems

